+### 4.D Recovery posture
 
-Not in scope to implement, but a follow-up worth tracking: if the
-persisted credential goes stale (admin rotated `EDEN_ADMIN_TOKEN`,
-the worker registry got rebuilt, etc.), the CLI surfaces a 401 at
-the next wire call and the operator must `rm
-/tmp/eden-manual/.credentials.json` and re-run. That recovery is
-documented in the skill docs' "troubleshooting" section in a
-future chunk; this chunk does not author it (one-pass scope
-discipline).
+With Decision 5's verify-and-reissue ladder, the CLI handles every
+common credential-staleness mode automatically: rerun of
+`setup-experiment.sh` (worker registry rebuilt), an admin running
+`reissue_credential` out-of-band, or a `/tmp/eden-manual/.credentials.json`
+that's been hand-edited or wiped all route to the reissue branch
+on the next CLI invocation. No operator cleanup is required.
 
+The one remaining mode that DOES require operator intervention:
+`EDEN_ADMIN_TOKEN` itself rotates (the admin secret in `.env`
+changed) AND the operator's persisted worker credential is also
+stale. The verify call fails with 401, the reissue call then fails
+with 401 (admin bearer is wrong), and the CLI exits with the wire
+error. Recovery: re-read `EDEN_ADMIN_TOKEN` from the live `.env`
+(the CLI's `_load_env` already does this) — usually the operator
+just needs to ensure they're running from the same checkout the
+stack was brought up against. This corner case is documented in
+the impl PR body and the skill docs as a one-line "if you see
+401-on-admin in the wire-error, your .env is stale" note.
+
